		<hr size="1">Hi, as a recent 31 shammy I have some input.  I started alchemy at 30, just recently, but I started it making sow potions.  Here's a tip for those shammies who are pressed for money.  I asked around and got a sponsor, a druid who bought me about 30 of each herb.  I had maxed my training points at the guild (22 skill) and began from there.  I made 4 skill points doing those 30 attempts and made 18 sow potions.  Ok so that ain't great, but it made them cost less than 8pp per potion to the druid who kept the potions.  He'll sell them easily in Kunark for a profit and I got four skill points.  I was so pleased with the potential of this ability that I bought 50pp worth of herbs and carried them around.  I ended up making 7 potions for a wizzie and recieved 107 pp for those potions.  100% profit margin, dam skippy.  I sold them for 15pp per potion, the extra 2pp was his way of saying thanks for being there with the potions.  <BR>    Shamen, this is an skill that is desperately needed by many, especially those at higher levels.  I was as skeptical of the worth of alchemy when I was younger as were some of the people who posted to this topic.  But now, I can see why they buy them, it's a real advantage to have a quick getaway, even to a sow caster like myself.  Most times I die it's because my sow ran out at a critical time.  A sow potion is definitely worth the lost time and exp, not to mention the humiliation of dying.  I plan to keep a potion in an empty inv slot and learn to rely on it being there in an emergency.   <BR>   Looking forward to GH potions and invis vs. undead.   <BR>   Gotta check out this skill further, it has enormous potential now that they lowered the herb cost by half (recently).  <BR>  <BR>Landragoran Heronwing<BR>Barbarian shaman of the 31st winter<BR>Lanys<br>&nbsp;<br>&nbsp;<br></font>
